codex: soft-default precedence + share config-rendering primitives

Extract the two genuinely-general helpers out of the codex wrapper into the
shared lib, and make the multi-agent defaults yield to a user's config.toml.

lib/util:
- attrs.flattenToDotted: nested attrset -> flat dotted-key attrset (leaf
  semantics match deep-merge: lists/derivations are leaves).
- toml.scalar: encode one Nix scalar as a TOML literal (scalars only; whole
  files use pkgs.formats.toml).
Both wired into ix (lib/default.nix). codex now composes them; only the
--config spelling and the forced/soft split stay package glue.

codex precedence: -c is codex's highest layer (above ~/.codex/config.toml),
so baking tunables via -c wrongly outranks a user's explicit config. Split:
- forcedSettings (check_for_update_on_startup): always -c, an invariant
  (read-only store binary can't self-update).
- settings (multi_agent_v2 cap 16, max_depth 3): SOFT defaults, injected only
  when the user's config.toml does not configure that sub-namespace, detected
  per second-segment token. A user's own later -c still wins over both.
The wrapper becomes a small shell script; passthru.tests.wrapper covers the
contract (forced always rides; soft injected when unset, withheld when the
user sets it; a comment mention does not gate; argv passthrough).

astlog: no-handrolled-toml-scalar flags a local `toToml` binding and points
to ix.toml.scalar / ix.attrs.flattenToDotted, with good/bad fixtures.

Verified: nix build .#codex and .#codex.tests.wrapper pass; astlog self-test
fires on bad / clears good; the rule finds 0 hits across all 405 .nix files;
changed files have 0 astlog violations.